description:
GloVe (Global Vectors for Word Representation) is a word embedding technique developed by Stanford researchers in 2014. It is a unsupervised learning algorithm for obtaining vector representations for words. GloVe works by using a co-occurrence matrix to calculate the probability of two words appearing together in a corpus. The matrix is then factorized to obtain the word vectors. The formula for GloVe is as follows:

P(w_i, w_j) = \frac{X_{ij}}{\sum_{k=1}^V X_{ik} \sum_{l=1}^V X_{jl}}

where X_{ij} is the number of times word i and word j appear together in the corpus, and V is the total number of words in the corpus.

